Hi there, A quick update! I've attached the custom code that our customer has running in their WooCommerce store theme's functions.php file, and I think there may be a WooCommerce 'hook' priority issue with the section shared below, as I believe Zamp's plugin utilizes the default priority of '10.' // Add Choice to Session
add_action( 'woocommerce_checkout_update_order_review', 'cb_checkout_donation_choice_set_session' );
function cb_checkout_donation_choice_set_session( $posted_data ) {
parse_str( $posted_data, $output );
if ( isset( $output['donation_choice'] ) ){
    WC()->session->set( 'donation_chosen', $output['donation_choice'] );
}
}

// for max 2 order 
add_filter('woocommerce_quantity_input_args', 'limit_product_quantity', 10, 2);
function limit_product_quantity($args, $product) {
$args['max_value'] = 2; // Set maximum quantity
$args['min_value'] = 1; // Set minimum quantity 
return $args;
}

add_action('woocommerce_after_cart_item_quantity_update', 'limit_cart_quantity', 10, 4);
function limit_cart_quantity($cart_item_key, $quantity, $cart_item, $cart) {
if ($quantity > 2) {
    WC()->cart->set_quantity($cart_item_key, 2);
    wc_add_notice(__('You can only purchase a maximum of 2 of this product.'), 'error');
}
} Normally, I'd suspect that the above code could cause duplicate tax to occur at checkout. However, the customer's technical resource noted that tax is still duplicated when this is disabled (he also had it disabled during our testing yesterday). I've also attached the plugin-zamp-tax.log files from today (8/6) and yesterday (8/5). The testing and items we worked through were at these times: 8/5 - 12:00 - 1:30 PM EST 8/6 - 1:30 - 2:30 PM EST Additionally, the customer's WooCommerce store status report is attached, including various versions, plugins, and other details. One other item I'm waiting on from our customer here is more information about their WordPress Database and if tax rates still exist in the tables noted below. This is a new area for me, and we appreciate any guidance on other places to look. wp_woocommerce_tax_rates wp_woocommerce_tax_rate_locations Lastly, a question: Would it be helpful if we shared the login credentials the customer provided for their WooCommerce store? If so, they've authorized us to share the access, and it is admin access; they ask that no changes be made.

